<font color="#FF0000">CANNON FODDER:  BAR TALES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 14 23:44:51 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Have you ever wandered into a bar and heard a bunch of folks  telling tall tales, when each person is expected to &quot;top this?&quot;  The tales, while perhaps having a shred of truth, begin to wander further and further from reality.  &quot;Cannon Fodder&quot; a self-published book by Phill Coleman that is heavily promoted on the Internet, may very well be a collection of those &quot;can you top this&quot; tales.  Told in a serious, straight forward manner, the book supposedly chronicles the term of military service of the author. Yet, in reading this work, one has to wonder if the author ever left a Chicago bar where GI's played &quot;can you to this.&quot; Oh, he has most of the names and places correct, but the devil is in the details, and this author has Mach 2 F-4 Phantoms making 90 degree climbs, from treetop level, so as to mark enemy emplacements with their afterburners.  In Phill's vietnam, there are buried communications closets located all through the jungles, so that lost special forces troop can call for help. In Phill's Vietnam, M-16 rifles can fire 2400 shots per minute, and the author routinely carries three such weapons, in the even one or more of them jams.
